COSO GEOTHERMAL POWER HOLDINGS, LLC MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
1. Availability. Coso Geothermal Power Holdings, LLC (Seller) makes electric energy and capacity available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale. Seller also makes available to any purchaser the ancillary services listed in this Paragraph 1:
RTO/ISO Specific
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (CAISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
Third Party Provider
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
2. Applicability: This Tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity, and ancillary services by Seller, which are (a) subject to the jurisdiction of the Commission, and (b) not made pursuant to another tariff on file with the Commission.
3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
5. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: The Commission granted Seller in Docket No. ER10-566-000 the following waivers and blanket authorization: (i) waiver of Parts 41, 101 and 141 of the Commission's regulations, except for 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations, except for Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; and (iii) blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumptions of liabilities. The qualifying facility status of Seller's small power production facilities was self-certified in Docket Nos. QF86-591, QF84-327, and QF86-590. 7. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Southwest region. Seller is a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Southwest Power Pool, Southeast, Northeast, Northwest, and Central regions.
8. Effective Date. This Tariff is effective on such date as set by the Commission.

CO-TENANCY AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
THIS AMENDED AND RESTATED CO-TENANCY AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this Agreement) is entered into and effective as of February 13, 2024 (the Effective Date), by and among Coso Battery Storage, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company as a Co-Tenant (as defined below) (Coso Battery), Mordor ES2 LLC, a Delaware limited liability company as Co-Tenant (as defined below) (Mordor ES2), Coso Transmission Line Partners, a California general partnership as a Co-Tenant (as defined below) (CTLP), CTLP in its role as the initial Manager (as defined below), and, solely for purposes of Sections 5.1(b) and (c), Coso Geothermal Power Holdings, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (CGPH) (Coso Battery, Mordor ES2, CTLP, and the Manager are each referred to herein individually as a Party, and collectively as the Parties).
RECITALS:
A. The United States of America, represented by various contracting officers previously entered into a certain contract, Contract No. N68711-05-C-0001 (the Navy Contract) with China Lake Joint Venture (CLJV). Pursuant to the Navy Contract, Navy granted to CLJV, among other rights, the right to develop electric power from the geothermal resources on public lands located in China Lake, California. CLJV transferred to Coso Energy Developers, a California partnership (CED) and CED subsequently transferred to Coso Power Developers, a California partnership (CPD), all rights, title, interests and obligations under the Navy Contract pertaining to those certain lands identified therein as the Navy II lands, including with respect to the Transmission Line (as defined below). Thereafter, CPD transferred to CTLP all rights, title, interests and obligations under the Navy Contract pertaining to the Transmission Line. In 2007, the ownership interests in CLJV, CPD, Coso Finance Partners, a California partnership, and CTLP transferred all of their respective rights, titles, interests and obligation under the Navy Contract to Coso Geothermal Contract Trust, a Delaware statutory trust (Contract Trust). On February 16, 2017, Contract Trust granted to CGPH all of Contract Trusts rights, title and interest and to perform all Contract Trusts obligations under the Navy Contract and to CTLP the right to use all of Contract Trusts rights and power necessary to retain ownership of or otherwise relate to the Transmission Line.
B. CGPH currently owns and operates that certain geothermal power facility with a total of nine, 30 MW turbine-generator sets, with an overall combined rated capacity of 270 MW located in China Lake, California (the Geothermal Project).
C. Coso Battery currently owns and operates a battery energy storage project, as further described in Exhibit A attached hereto (the Coso Battery Storage Project), located in the vicinity of a portion of the Geothermal Project on property known as BLM West leased from the U.S. Bureau of Land Management (BLM) pursuant to the BLM Lease (as defined below).
1 D. BLM approved an amendment to the existing Plan of Operations for the Geothermal Project to construct and operate Coso Battery Storage Project on the BLM West property under that certain Geothermal Sundry Notice, submitted as of February 14, 2020 and approved as of May 18, 2020.
E. On August 4, 2020, Coso Battery, CTLP, and CGPH entered into that certain Co- Tenancy and Shared Facilities Agreement (Prior Agreement) under which Coso Battery subsequently exercised its Option (as defined in the Prior Agreement) to acquire the Coso Battery Project Undivided Interest (as defined below).
F. Mordor ES2 is now developing and will own and operate a 20 megawatt (MW) battery energy storage project, as further described on Exhibit B attached hereto (the Mordor ES2 Battery Storage Project), that will be located in the vicinity of a portion of the Geothermal Project on property known as BLM West leased from the U.S. Bureau of Land Management (BLM) pursuant to the BLM Lease (as defined below).
G. Coso Battery provided its consent, required under Section 5.1(b) of the Prior Agreement, to allow Mordor ES2 to develop the Mordor ES2 Battery Storage Project and interconnect to the Shared Facilities, in that certain Coso - Consent to Tie-in of a New 20 MW BESS dated as of the date hereof.
H. Coso Battery has entered into that certain Partial Sub-Assignment and Assumption Agreement with CGPH, dated June 29, 2020 and amended as of the date hereof, under which CGPH has assigned to Coso Battery certain rights under the BLM Lease, including the rights to the License for an Electrical Power Plant Site Utilizing Geothermal Resources, Site License No. CA-25690, entered into on March 29, 2019, by BLM, as the licensor, and Coso Operating Company LLC, as the licensee on behalf of CGPH (the BLM 25690 Site License), non-exclusive easement for access for the purposes of the placement of the Coso Battery Project Interconnection Facilities and any other associated project authorizations, necessary for Coso Battery to construct, own, operate, and maintain the Coso Battery Storage Project (the Coso Battery Partial Sub Agreement).
I. In connection with the Geothermal Project, CTLP owns that certain approximately 28.8 mile, 230 Kv radial transmission line, together with all associated permits and other authorizations necessary and appropriate to operate and maintain the transmission line, as further described in Exhibit C attached hereto (the Transmission Line) through which electricity produced by the Geothermal Project is transmitted for delivery to the transmission system owned by Southern California Edison Company (SCE) and controlled by the California Independent System Operator Corporation (CAISO). CTLP owns and operates the Transmission Line in accordance with terms and conditions set forth in the Amended and Restated General Partnership Agreement of CTLP, dated as of July 25, 1989, as amended by that First Amendment dated as of December 16, 1992, Amendment No. 2 dated December 7, 2007, and Amendment No. 3 dated December 2013.
2 J. Coso Battery has entered into that certain Partial Sub-Sub Assignment and Assumption Agreement, dated as of August 4, 2020 with CTLP, under which CTLP has assigned to Coso Battery certain additional rights associated with the Transmission Line and a construction easement (as well as other rights) (the Coso Battery Partial Sub-Sub Agreement).
K. Each of CED or CPD (as applicable), SCE and CAISO is a party to those certain (i) Large Generator Interconnection Agreement, dated June 3, 2011 and (ii) Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement, dated December 8, 2009 (each as amended, restated or otherwise modified from time to time, an Interconnection Agreement and collectively, the Interconnection Agreements) under which CGPH (as assignee of CED and CPD) and Coso Battery have interconnection rights and rights to use certain interconnection facilities described therein.
L. All rights and obligations with respect to the Transmission Line are referred to herein as the Shared Facilities.
M. Coso Battery, CTLP, and, should it exercise the Option (as defined below), Mordor ES2, will share in obligations relating to, and certain costs of, the Shared Facilities in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement.
N. Upon the Effective Date of this Agreement, the Prior Agreement shall be deemed amended and restated and superseded and replaced in its entirety by this Agreement and of no further force or effect.
O. Coso Battery, Mordor ES2, and CTLP also wish to appoint CTLP as the Manager for the provision of certain services with respect to the Shared Facilities at such time and on the terms and conditions contained herein. The Manager obtains services through that certain Operations and Maintenance Agreement, dated as of August 17, 2017 (together with any replacement thereof, O&M Agreement), between Managers affiliates, CED, Coso Finance Partners, CPD, CGPH, and Coso Operating Company LLC (together with any assignee, successor or replacement thereof, Operator) under which Operator provides services necessary for Manager to perform its obligations as Manager hereunder.

20 obligations under, the O&M Agreement that relate to this Agreement, and will not reduce or alter such obligations, rights or remedies in a manner that materially impacts the performance of the Managers obligations hereunder without the consent of Coso Battery.

If any Co-Tenant responsible for the imposition of a Lien (other than a Permitted Lien) fails to discharge promptly any such Lien, the other Co-Tenants, in addition to any other rights it may have at law or equity for a breach of this Agreement, shall have the right to notify the responsible Co-Tenant in writing and to take any reasonable action to satisfy, defend, settle or otherwise remove the Lien at the responsible Co-Tenants expense.

A Co-Tenant shall not be required to provide any such prior notice when accessing the Shared Facilities to respond to and address an Emergency, but such Co-Tenant shall provide notice of access to, and coordinate with, the Manager and the other Co-Tenants as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter.
21 6.2 Taxes. 22 of matters affecting the Shared Facilities in accordance with the terms of this Agreement. (a) As of the Effective Date (or, with respect to Mordor ES2, on and after the Closing Date) line losses that occur over the Shared Facilities while Co- Tenants are using the Shared Facilities to transmit energy shall be allocated as determined by CAISO.
(b) Any interruption, reduction in deliveries of, or other curtailment of electrical power through the Shared Facilities, or to the point of interconnection designated in the Interconnection Agreements, in each case instructed by the CAISO, shall be allocated to one or more Co-Tenants as CAISO shall determine and apportion to such Co-Tenants. If and only to the extent that CAISO does not
24 determine and apportion such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power, the Manager shall, to the fullest extent possible allocate such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power to the Co-Tenant whose actions or inactions caused such interruption, reduction, or curtailment; provided, if and to the extent such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power cannot be attributed to the actions or inactions of any Co-Tenant, the Manager shall allocate such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power to each Co-Tenant in proportion to its respective Projects actual or scheduled output (in the case of each Battery Storage Project, its discharge output), if any, at the time of such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power (which shall be determined, to the extent applicable, based on the Projects respective output actually scheduled in the day-ahead or real-time market); provided further, if and to the extent such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power cannot be allocated in proportion to the respective Projects actual or scheduled output (such as when the Manager cannot reasonably determine what the output of either Project would have been during the duration of such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment had such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment had not occurred), the Manager shall allocate such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power to each Co-Tenant in proportion to its respective Projects Percentage Interest. 29 relate to errors discovered and disclosed within the inspection and audit period provided for in this provision.
7.6 Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget. On or before November 30th of each year, the Manager shall provide each Co-Tenant with a draft of (i) the annual budget for the Shared Facilities for the immediately following calendar year and (ii) the annual operating plan setting forth the underlying assumptions and implementation plans for such budget (the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget). The Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget will include a separate operating budget and capital budget and will set forth, in reasonable detail, anticipated operations plans and costs, including forecasts of electricity production and corresponding usage of major commodities, repairs and capital improvements (including major maintenance and a cost/benefits analysis for proposed capital improvements), Scheduled Outages, routine maintenance and overhaul schedules, procurement (including equipment acquisitions and spare parts and consumable inventories indicating a breakdown of capital items and expense items), staffing, personnel and labor activities (including unit rates for labor and holidays to be observed), administrative activities, data regarding other work proposed to be undertaken by the Manager and regarding expected environmental performance, together with an itemized estimate of all Shared Expenses to be incurred in connection therewith. Items in the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget will be divided and identified as (a) target budget items and (b) non-target budget items, which are items over which the Manager has little or no control. Each Co-Tenant may submit any comments or questions to the Manager within thirty (30) days of receipt of the draft Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget. The Manager shall incorporate any comments received and shall provide a final Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget to the Co-Tenants by January 15th of the following year for approval by unanimous vote of the Co-Tenants. If, by the first day of any calendar year, the Co-Tenants and the Manager are unable to reach agreement concerning any portion of the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget for such calendar year, such Dispute will be submitted for resolution in accordance with the Dispute resolution procedures set forth in Section 14.18. Pending the outcome of such Dispute resolution process and amendment of the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget to reflect such outcome for purposes of the remainder of such calendar year, the portion of the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget that is in Dispute will be resolved by using the portion of the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget as proposed by the Manager for such disputed portion. The Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget may be amended during the year by unanimous vote of the Co-Tenants.

Exhibit A
Description of Coso Battery Storage Project
A battery energy storage system (BESS) encompassing approximately 4 acres will be added to the existing well pad infrastructure maintained by Coso Geothermal Power Holdings, LLC and operated by Coso Operating Company LLC. The BESS will be located within the confines of Well Pad 46-19, which is within the fenced confines of the existing BLM-West geothermal power plant. The geothermal well field is on the BLM Lease in the Coso Known Geothermal Resources Area (KGRA) within the confines of Naval Air Weapons Station (NAWS) China Lake, in Inyo County, California. The BESS site is entirely located on a BLM Lease on withdrawn public lands, managed by the U.S. Navy. The BESS will deliver 60 megawatts (MW) and store up to 240 megawatt hours (MWh) of electricity for delivery into the local Southern California Energy (SCE) grid via the Kramer Junction Substation. The addition of the BESS to the well pads and power plant area will also require adding an underground 35 kilovolt (kV) distribution line, and overhead 35kV distribution lines to connect the BESS to the BLM-West Substation. The distribution lines will connect into a new switchyard adjacent to an existing substation on disturbed land within the existing geothermal power plant boundary. Construction activities will occur over an 8- to 9-month period.
Exhibit B
Description of Mordor ES2 Battery Storage Project
20 MW battery energy storage (BESS) project located on previously disturbed lands at existing Coso Geothermal Power plant. The Mordor 2 Project (Mordor 2) includes the installation of Tesla Megapack system with a total of 26 Megapacks to be initially installed. Megapack includes internal inverters and total of 4 Megapacks will be connected in a parallel formation to form a single feeder through pad-mount transformers rated at 5 MVA. The power from three interties will accumulate at 13.8 kV switchgear and will be connected to the existing 220 kV transmission line through a 230/13.8 kV transformer. This new BESS will connect to SCEs 220kV Kramer Substation through the existing tie line at 220 kV.
